.SH NAME
Bitcoin::Crypto::Secret \- Storing secrets more safely
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 1
\&        use Bitcoin::Crypto::Secret;
\&
\&        my $secret = Bitcoin::Crypto::Secret\->new(\*(Aqsuper secret password\*(Aq);
\&        say $secret; # prints "[REDACTED]"
\&
\&        # format strings are ok
\&        my $secret_with_format = Bitcoin::Crypto::Secret\->new([hex => \*(Aq...\*(Aq]);
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This is a small class which improves the security of secrets stored in Perl
memory. It is an inside\-out object which always stringifies to \f(CW\*(C`[REDACTED]\*(C'\fR,
so that the secret will not get leaked accidentally, for example in dumps (like
Data::Dumper). Bitcoin::Crypto uses this class to store secrets internally,
\&\fBregardless of whether you use it explicitly or not\fR. Plainstring secrets will
be turned into instances of Bitcoin::Crypto::Secret automatically.
.PP
Secrets returned from Bitcoin::Crypto functions are plain strings \fBand not
instances of Bitcoin::Crypto::Secret\fR.
.SS "What is considered a secret?"
.IX Subsection "What is considered a secret?"
Currently, following arguments to functions accept objects of
Bitcoin::Crypto::Secret:
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW$mnemonic\fR and \f(CW$password\fR in "from_mnemonic" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::ExtPrivate
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW$seed\fR in "from_seed" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::ExtPrivate
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW$serialized\fR in "from_serialized" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::ExtPrivate
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW$wif\fR in "from_wif" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::Private
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW$serialized\fR in "from_serialized" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::Private
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW$wif\fR in "validate_wif" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Util
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW$entropy\fR in "mnemonic_from_entropy" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Util
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW$mnemonic\fR and \f(CW$password\fR in "mnemonic_to_seed" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Util
.SS "Crypt::SecretBuffer awareness and partial compatibility"
.IX Subsection "Crypt::SecretBuffer awareness and partial compatibility"
This class is partially compatible with Crypt::SecretBuffer: the interface
of "new" and "unmask_to" is the same. In addition, it stringifies to the
same \f(CW\*(C`[REDACTED]\*(C'\fR string. You can think of Bitcoin::Crypto::Secret as
"Crypt::SecretBuffer light", as it only tries to hide the secret from leaking
by accident, and not keep it away from perl\*(Aqs heap entirely. \fBThere is no way
to keep secrets away from perl\*(Aqs heap\fR when using Bitcoin::Crypto, as the
library manipulates the secrets with perl (non\-XS) code.
.PP
That being said, if you want that little extra protection or other features of
Crypt::SecretBuffer, Bitcoin::Crypto is aware of its existence and will
accept its objects in any place where a secret is expected. It will not try to
turn it into a Bitcoin::Crypto::Secret instance, but instead store it
internally as\-is.
.PP
In order to use Crypt::SecretBuffer with Bitcoin::Crypto, it must be version
\&\f(CW0.007\fR or greater, as this version introduced the \f(CW\*(C`unmask_to\*(C'\fR method.
.SH INTERFACE
.IX Header "INTERFACE"
.SS Methods
.IX Subsection "Methods"
\fInew\fR
.IX Subsection "new"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $secret = $class\->new($data)
.Ve
.PP
Creates a new secret instance holding \f(CW$data\fR, which can be any defined value
(unlike "new" in Crypt::SecretBuffer, which only accepts strings).
.PP
\fIunmask_to\fR
.IX Subsection "unmask_to"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $ret = $secret\->unmask_to($sub)
.Ve
.PP
Executes \f(CW$sub\fR with a sole argument being a value of the secret. Returns
whatever \f(CW$sub\fR returned. Fully compatible with
"unmask_to" in Crypt::SecretBuffer.
.PP
\fIas_string\fR
.IX Subsection "as_string"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $str = $secret\->as_string()
.Ve
.PP
Always returns \f(CW\*(C`[REDACTED]\*(C'\fR. This happens automatically on object
stringification. Unlike Crypt::SecretBuffer, there is no way to disable this
mark to make it stringify as the secret. If this is needed, this idiom can be
used:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $data = $secret\->unmask_to(sub { shift });
.Ve
